1.1. Problem Formulation¶

Exploring the data to address the following questions:

  • What percentage of customers churn, and what percentage stay active?
  • Are there any patterns in churn based on tariff plans?
  • Are there any discernible patterns or preferences in churn based on customer behavior?
  • How can we segment customers at risk of churn?

#Histogram charts for numerical columns

#Define histogram plotting functions
def chart(feature, frame, color='red'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    sns.histplot(frame[feature], bins=20, kde=True, color=color)
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {feature}') #Replace column names for each chart
    plt.xlabel(f'{feature}')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.show()

numerical_cols = ['CallFailure', 'SubscriptionLength', 'SecondsofUse', 'Frequencyofuse', 'FrequencyofSMS', 'DistinctCalledNumbers', 'CustomerValue']

for feat in numerical_cols:
    chart(feat, df)

2.3. Posing one meaningful question and exploring the data¶

Do Higher customer value indicate more loyal and engaged customers who are less likely to churn

In [22]:
#Define higher and lower customer value groups
higher_value = df[df['CustomerValue'] >= df['CustomerValue'].median()]
lower_value = df[df['CustomerValue'] < df['CustomerValue'].median()]

#Calculate churn counts for each group
churn_higher = higher_value['Churn'].sum()
churn_lower = lower_value['Churn'].sum()
nobs_higher = len(higher_value)
nobs_lower = len(lower_value)

#Perform z-test for proportions
count = [churn_higher, churn_lower]
nobs = [nobs_higher, nobs_lower]
stat, pval = proportions_ztest(count, nobs)
alpha = 0.05

#Print results
print("Z-test statistic:", stat)
print("p-value:", pval)
if pval < alpha:
    print("Reject null hypothesis: There is a significant difference in churn rates between higher and lower value groups.")
else:
    print("Fail to reject null hypothesis: There is no significant difference in churn rates between higher and lower value groups.")

Z-test statistic: -15.673332702578461
p-value: 2.3018632129503478e-55
Reject null hypothesis: There is a significant difference in churn rates between higher and lower value groups.

#Label encoding

def object_to_int(dataframe_series):
    # Check if the data type of the series is 'object'
    if dataframe_series.dtype == 'object':
        # If the data type is 'object', transform it to integer using LabelEncoder
        dataframe_series = LabelEncoder().fit_transform(dataframe_series)
    return dataframe_series

#Apply the object_to_int function to each column in the DataFrame
df = df.apply(lambda x: object_to_int(x))

#SMOTE function
def apply_smote(X_train, y_train):
    #Transform the dataset
    oversample = SMOTE()
    X_train_smote, y_train_smote = oversample.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
    
    #Print class distribution after SMOTE
    print("Class distribution after applying SMOTE:")
    print(Counter(y_train_smote))
    
    return X_train_smote, y_train_smote

#Apply SMOTE to each suite
X_train_smote1, y_train_smote1 = apply_smote(X_train1, y_train1)
X_train_smote2, y_train_smote2 = apply_smote(X_train2, y_train2)
X_train_smote3, y_train_smote3 = apply_smote(X_train3, y_train3)

#Function to find the best k
def find_best_k(X_train_smote, y_train_smote):
    #Define parameters
    param_grid = {'n_neighbors': [1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 15]}

    #Instantiate KNN Classifier
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier()

    #Apply GridSearchCV
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(knn, param_grid, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')

    #Fit data
    grid_search.fit(X_train_smote, y_train_smote)

    #Get best parameters
    best_params = grid_search.best_params_

    return best_params['n_neighbors']

#Find the best k for each SMOTE-applied suite
best_k_suite1 = find_best_k(X_train_smote1, y_train_smote1)
best_k_suite2 = find_best_k(X_train_smote2, y_train_smote2)
best_k_suite3 = find_best_k(X_train_smote3, y_train_smote3)

#Instantiate KNN with the best k for each suite
best_knn_suite1 = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=best_k_suite1)
best_knn_suite2 = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=best_k_suite2)
best_knn_suite3 = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=best_k_suite3)

#Fit the KNN models and evaluate for each suite
best_knn_suite1.fit(X_train_smote1, y_train_smote1)
accuracy_suite1 = best_knn_suite1.score(X_test1, y_test1)

best_knn_suite2.fit(X_train_smote2, y_train_smote2)
accuracy_suite2 = best_knn_suite2.score(X_test2, y_test2)

best_knn_suite3.fit(X_train_smote3, y_train_smote3)
accuracy_suite3 = best_knn_suite3.score(X_test3, y_test3)

#Print results
print("Best k for Suite 1:", best_k_suite1)
print("Accuracy for Suite 1:", accuracy_suite1)

print("Best k for Suite 2:", best_k_suite2)
print("Accuracy for Suite 2:", accuracy_suite2)

print("Best k for Suite 3:", best_k_suite3)
print("Accuracy for Suite 3:", accuracy_suite3)

#Function to train and evaluate a random forest classifier
def train_and_evaluate_rf(X_train_rf, y_train_rf, X_test_rf, y_test_rf):

    #Define parameters for GridSearch
    grid_space = {'max_depth': [3, 5, 10, None],
                  'n_estimators': [10, 20, 30],
                  'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy']}
    
    #Instantiate random forest classifier
    rf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)

    #Apply GridSearchCV
    rf_grid = GridSearchCV(rf, param_grid=grid_space, scoring='accuracy', cv=5)
    rf_grid.fit(X_train_rf, y_train_rf)

    #Get best parameters
    best_params_rf = rf_grid.best_params_

    #Instantiate random forest with best parameters
    best_rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=best_params_rf['n_estimators'],
                                      max_depth=best_params_rf['max_depth'],
                                      criterion=best_params_rf['criterion'],
                                      random_state=42)

    #Train the random forest classifier
    best_rf.fit(X_train_rf, y_train_rf)

    #Make predictions
    y_pred_rf = best_rf.predict(X_test_rf)

    #Predict probability for positive class
    y_pred_prob_rf = best_rf.predict_proba(X_test_rf)[:, 1]

    #Evaluate performance metrics
    accuracy_rf = accuracy_score(y_test_rf, y_pred_rf)
    precision_rf = precision_score(y_test_rf, y_pred_rf)
    recall_rf = recall_score(y_test_rf, y_pred_rf)
    f1_rf = f1_score(y_test_rf, y_pred_rf)
    conf_matrix_rf = confusion_matrix(y_test_rf, y_pred_rf)
    classification_rep_rf = classification_report(y_test_rf, y_pred_rf)


    #Plot confusion matrix
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))
    sns.heatmap(conf_matrix_rf, annot=True, fmt="d", linecolor="k", linewidths=3)
    plt.title("Confusion Matrix", fontsize=14)
    plt.show()

    #Print evaluation results
    print("Random Forest Classifier Evaluation:")
    print("Best Parameters:", best_params_rf)
    print("Classification accuracy:", accuracy_rf)
    print("Precision:", precision_rf)
    print("Recall:", recall_rf)
    print("F1 Score:", f1_rf)
    print("Classification Report:\n", classification_rep_rf)
    print("Confusion Matrix:\n", conf_matrix_rf)

    return accuracy_rf, precision_rf, recall_rf, f1_rf, conf_matrix_rf

#Define the suites with their corresponding datasets
suites_rf = [(X_train_smote1, y_train_smote1, X_test1, y_test1),
             (X_train_smote2, y_train_smote2, X_test2, y_test2),
             (X_train_smote3, y_train_smote3, X_test3, y_test3)]

#Define lists to store evaluation results
accuracy_list_rf = []
precision_list_rf = []
recall_list_rf = []
f1_list_rf = []
conf_matrix_list_rf = []

#Iterate over each suite, train and evaluate the random forest classifier
for i, (X_train_rf, y_train_rf, X_test_rf, y_test_rf) in enumerate(suites_rf):
    print(f"Suite {i + 1} Evaluation:")
    accuracy_rf, precision_rf, recall_rf, f1_rf, conf_matrix_rf = train_and_evaluate_rf(X_train_rf, y_train_rf, X_test_rf, y_test_rf)
    #Append evaluation results to lists
    accuracy_list_rf.append(accuracy_rf)
    precision_list_rf.append(precision_rf)
    recall_list_rf.append(recall_rf)
    f1_list_rf.append(f1_rf)
    conf_matrix_list_rf.append(conf_matrix_rf)
    print("\n")

rf_metrics = {
    'Accuracy': 0.914,
    'Precision': 0.715,
    'Recall': 0.747,
    'F1 Score': 0.731
}

#Performance metrics for KNN
knn_metrics = {
    'Accuracy': 0.908,
    'Precision': 0.661,
    'Recall': 0.843,
    'F1 Score': 0.741
}

#Extract metric names and values
metrics = list(rf_metrics.keys())
rf_values = list(rf_metrics.values())
knn_values = list(knn_metrics.values())

# Set position of bar on X axis
r1 = range(len(metrics))
r2 = [x + 0.35 for x in r1]

# Create grouped bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.bar(r1, rf_values, color='#ff6666', width=0.35, edgecolor='grey', label='Random Forest')
plt.bar(r2, knn_values, color='#66b3ff', width=0.35, edgecolor='grey', label='KNN')
plt.xlabel('Performance Metrics', fontweight='bold')
plt.xticks([r + 0.35/2 for r in range(len(metrics))], metrics)
plt.ylabel('Score', fontweight='bold')
plt.title('Comparison of Classification Models')
plt.legend()

# Add values on top of each bar
for i, value in enumerate(rf_values):
    plt.text(i, value, str(value), ha='center', va='bottom')
for i, value in enumerate(knn_values):
    plt.text(i + 0.35, value, str(value), ha='center', va='bottom')

# Show plot
plt.show()
